CVE-2011-5000.summary: The ssh_gssapi_parse_ename function in gss-serv.c in OpenSSH 5.8 and earlier, when gssapi-with-mic authentication is enabled, allows remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (memory consumption) via a large value in a certain length field.  NOTE: there may be limited scenarios in which this issue is relevant.

CVE-2017-15906.summary: The process_open function in sftp-server.c in OpenSSH before 7.6 does not properly prevent write operations in readonly mode, which allows attackers to create zero-length files.

CVE-2014-1692.summary: The hash_buffer function in schnorr.c in OpenSSH through 6.4, when Makefile.inc is modified to enable the J-PAKE protocol, does not initialize certain data structures, which might allow remote attackers to cause a denial of service (memory corruption) or have unspecified other impact via vectors that trigger an error condition.

CVE-2010-5107.summary: The default configuration of OpenSSH through 6.1 enforces a fixed time limit between establishing a TCP connection and completing a login, which makes it easier for remote attackers to cause a denial of service (connection-slot exhaustion) by periodically making many new TCP connections.

CVE-2018-15473.summary: OpenSSH through 7.7 is prone to a user enumeration vulnerability due to not delaying bailout for an invalid authenticating user until after the packet containing the request has been fully parsed, related to auth2-gss.c, auth2-hostbased.c, and auth2-pubkey.c.

CVE-2016-10708.summary: sshd in OpenSSH before 7.4 allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service (NULL pointer dereference and daemon crash) via an out-of-sequence NEWKEYS message, as demonstrated by Honggfuzz, related to kex.c and packet.c.

CVE-2010-4478.summary: OpenSSH 5.6 and earlier, when J-PAKE is enabled, does not properly validate the public parameters in the J-PAKE protocol, which allows remote attackers to bypass the need for knowledge of the shared secret, and successfully authenticate, by sending crafted values in each round of the protocol, a related issue to CVE-2010-4252.

CVE-2016-0777.summary: The resend_bytes function in roaming_common.c in the client in OpenSSH 5.x, 6.x, and 7.x before 7.1p2 allows remote servers to obtain sensitive information from process memory by requesting transmission of an entire buffer, as demonstrated by reading a private key.

CVE-2011-4327.summary: ssh-keysign.c in ssh-keysign in OpenSSH before 5.8p2 on certain platforms executes ssh-rand-helper with unintended open file descriptors, which allows local users to obtain sensitive key information via the ptrace system call.

CVE-2010-4755.summary: The (1) remote_glob function in sftp-glob.c and the (2) process_put function in sftp.c in OpenSSH 5.8 and earlier, as used in FreeBSD 7.3 and 8.1, NetBSD 5.0.2, OpenBSD 4.7, and other products, allow remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (CPU and memory consumption) via crafted glob expressions that do not match any pathnames, as demonstrated by glob expressions in SSH_FXP_STAT requests to an sftp daemon, a different vulnerability than CVE-2010-2632.

CVE-2012-0814.summary: The auth_parse_options function in auth-options.c in sshd in OpenSSH before 5.7 provides debug messages containing authorized_keys command options, which allows remote authenticated users to obtain potentially sensitive information by reading these messages, as demonstrated by the shared user account required by Gitolite.  NOTE: this can cross privilege boundaries because a user account may intentionally have no shell or filesystem access, and therefore may have no supported way to read an authorized_keys file in its own home directory.

Client Feedback

  • Lisa had to contend with my 3 young children invading her home for prints. She made us feel very welcome and was wonderful with the children. My 3 year old still talks about getting her fingerprints and hand prints done there. The clocks look amazing and I cannot wait to see the Grandparents faces when they see them. Lisa does all of the work herself, none of it is sent off like some other similar businesses, and she takes a real pride in her work.

    K. Bridle, Thatcham

  • Lisa has made me so many things from Christmas baubles to silver cufflinks and everything she has done has been superb! She puts so much care and effort into making everything absolutely perfect. The items make great gifts and I will continue to use her going forward. Recently I needed an item more urgently and unfortunately had to go elsewhere for a mug. In comparison the mug is not a patch on Lisa’s work – next time I will be more organised and make sure I get myself into Camps!

    S. Dolan, Newbury

  • So impressed with the beautiful pieces available; I cannot wait till my jewellery arrives. I was very impressed with the quick and easy print taking of my 16 week old daughters hand and foot ready for daddy’s surprise Christmas pressie. I also ordered two silver charms for myself; daughters handprint & my dogs paw print. Next event I shall be ordering some ceramics; ideal Christmas presents for the family from my daughter. Friendly & professional service – thank you Lisa. You come highly recommended!

    K. Carter, Thatcham

  • I absolutely love Lisa’s work so decided when my second child was born to get my cats print done as well. He’s a huge part of our family. The process itself has to be simple for me as I’m in Luxembourg so can’t exactly bring my cats paw to Lisa or visa versa! Also my cat is very feisty. So a quick wipe of his paw, put it on some paper & he can walk away oblivious, was perfect. I wear my amazing ‘charms’ every day.

    A. Hemmett, Luxembourg

  • I was over the moon with the plate and tiles I purchased from Cheeky Little Prints. The workmanship (or should I say womanship!) was outstanding and the service was second only to the welcome I received with my newborn son and daughter who is definitely going through the terrible 2 ‘ s. Will return for more products and will definitely recommend!!

    A. Pimble, Swindon

  • I hosted a print party with Lisa. We were all very impressed with her professionalism, the attention to detail, care and her high expectations just came as standard. However, it was her flexibility for individual design, accommodation with delivery of products and the quality of the finished results which blew me away. Everyone was extremely happy with their ceramics and silver alike! Thank you Lisa!

    O. Beard, Watchfield, Shrivenham

  • Just wanted to say thank you for my charm.  I absolutely love it!  It’s no replacement for Benzy but it’s lovely to know I can carry a piece of him around with me, thank you! I will do Aston’s at some point in the not too distant future and send his prints to you as well.  Thanks again.

    L. Bohlin, Norwich

  • Absolutely Brilliant! Lisa was amazing from start to finish. We are delighted with our paw print charms, they mean so much to us after losing our little dog. She was really helpful and informative. She even used different prints so that our charms were personal to us. I had a look around before choosing Cheeky Little Prints and I’m very glad I did. Lisa was amazing and she makes the print bigger than others I’ve seen. I will definitely be recommending her to everyone!  Thank you so much!

    H. New, Bristol

  • My necklace has arrived safe and sound 🙂 I can’t even begin to put in words how beautiful it is! I feel quite emotional about it, it is so very special!! I was wondering if it might be possible if I find a print that is good enough? My old girl I lost a few years ago used to do paw prints onto birthday cards 🙂 I am sure I still have them to have her paw as well!! Thank you so much Lisa <3 This has to be the most precious piece of jewellery I now have <3 it is so beautiful and it’s so easy to see which paw print charm belongs to which dog! I will treasure it always xx such wonderful work xx

    H. Ward, Snaith
